05286nam a22006495i 9780814760925DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20142014nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147609257 a10.18574/nyu/9780814760925.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)679305  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aUB418.C45 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a306.09222/ger1 aShepler, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aChildhood Deployed :bRemaking Child Soldiers in Sierra Leone /cSusan Shepler. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Figures and Tables -- tList of Acronyms -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- t1. Youth in Sierra Leone -- t2. Child Protection Deployed -- t3. Learning "Child Soldier" across Contexts -- t4. Informal Reintegrators, Communities, and NGOs -- t5. Distinctions in the Population of "Child Soldiers": RUF and CDF, Boys and Girls -- tConclusion -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aChildhood Deployed examines the reintegration of former child soldiers in Sierra Leone. Based on eighteen months of participant-observer ethnographic fieldwork and ten years of follow-up research, the book argues that there is a fundamental disconnect between the Western idea of the child soldier and the individual lived experiences of the child soldiers of Sierra Leone. Susan Shepler contends that the reintegration of former child soldiers is a political process having to do with changing notions of childhood as one of the central structures of society.For most Westerners the tragedy of the idea of "child soldier" centers around perceptions of lost and violated innocence. In contrast, Shepler finds that for most Sierra Leoneans, the problem is not lost innocence but the horror of being separated from one's family and the resulting generational break in youth education. Further, Shepler argues that Sierra Leonean former child soldiers find themselves forced to strategically perform (or refuse to perform) as the"child soldier" Western human rights initiatives expect in order to most effectively gain access to the resources available for their social reintegration. The strategies don't always work-in some cases, Shepler finds, Western human rights initiatives do more harm than good. While this volume focuses on the well-known case of child soldiers in Sierra Leone, it speaks to the larger concerns of childhood studies with a detailed ethnography of people struggling over the situated meaning of the categories of childhood.It offers an example of the cultural politics of childhood in action, in which the very definition of childhood is at stake and an important site of political contestation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChild soldierszSierra LeonexReintegration. 0aChild soldierszSierra Leone. 0aChildren and warzSierra Leone. 70(DE-588)4000197-00(DE-627)10640184X0(DE-576)208837302aAbrüstung2gnd 70(DE-588)4028859-60(DE-627)1044191990(DE-576)208979859aJugend2gnd 70(DE-588)4028935-70(DE-627)1062764410(DE-576)20898013XaJugendschutz2gnd 70(DE-588)4030550-80(DE-627)1043601000(DE-576)208988165aKind2gnd 70(DE-588)4032081-90(DE-627)1062629710(DE-576)208995544aKonflikt2gnd 70(DE-588)4055409-00(DE-627)1046889630(DE-576)209113723aSoldat2gnd 70(DE-588)4077570-70(DE-627)1060797510(DE-576)209205660aSoziale Integration2gnd 70(DE-588)4112646-40(DE-627)1058356840(DE-576)209469684aAu